segments.text: ¿Dónde será?
Sus tías en la escuela.
Ah, sí.
Esa familia venía, vino de otros estados.
Y esa familia estaba vecina con nosotros.
Ellos desmontaron ese lugar.
Nosotros estábamos como aquí.
Esa familia llegó y compró el lugar.
Era monte.
Enfrente de nosotros.
Eran el papá y la mamá.
Y dos muchachas, que eran sus hijas de ellos.
Bueno, ya los señores estaban poco grandes.
Esas muchachas eran muchachas ya mayores, nomás que ellas nunca se habían casado.
Esas muchachas, ni nosotros ni ellas entendían, pero era buena familia.
Then, as chance would have it, she said she was going to be a teacher.
Nosotros conocíamos por mi papá, ese señor que vive también por ese camino, le decían Steary Well.
Ese señor era un trabajador y era un señor solo, americano.
Y él, yo no sé cómo se hacía entender con mi papá, pero pues sería por sus modos.
Él tenía muy buenas amistades con la gente.
American.
And that man also looked for my father a lot.
This boy, he was already a big boy, but he hadn't been married.
Those girls arrived there for new ones.
They liked it.
So these girls went out for a walk.
I saw that they dressed very well.
And those boys came and took them for a walk.
And my father would say, this is Tiri Güell, he says, he's taking the girls for a walk.
And I would hear my father talking.
And they would go.
And another time they would say, they would go to a carnival with them and everything.
Then the other sister got married to another boy, also of an older American age, who was called Güelle.
Willie Hatchick.
Willie Hatchick.
Sí, yo no sé, será apelativo, yo no sé, pero así le decían a él, el Willie.
Entonces, ella salía con ese muchacho, la otra muchacha.
Then came the time that she went to school.
And I was her friend, because we were neighbors.
She said, you here?
And I said, my friend, yes.
Oh, she was very pleased.
Well, what do you think?
What I learned, my memory,
I think my memory has been very bad.
Well, I don't think it's that bad because I'm saying all this, but now I've always lost it.
Well, then she gave me a book.
You know the books that were there before.
Look, this story was the story that I learned.
I learned to do the first numbers because I never knew anything.
The 2, the 5, I only know up to the 60.
Yes, I know them all.
But the ones I have the most are the 80, 60.
Well, I was learning that because she taught me.
Then she gave me a little book and I started writing letters.
Well, I did write them and I did learn.
And she told me, I learned them in English.
Maybe if I had followed, I would have learned.
So I told them in English.
Well, I always kept them.
Los conocí, los conozco, y conozco todo, y sé leer español poquito, y bueno, pues yo estuve un mes en la escuela.
Entonces me dio un librito que decía mi acuerdo, lo sabría de memoria, pero no, lo supe leer y conocí las letras, y donde este era un niño, y ese niño se trataba de su, yo creo que,
of what he, his name, and Yasina, right?
And he was called Will.
Well, and I said, this is Will, how do you do, Will?
That's the story he had, and she told me that.
And how do you do, May?
How do you do, May?
And she, well, so I said,
Well, no.
Since my mother got sick, when I was in school for a month, I had to leave school.
Then they took me out of school because she had babies of all sizes, and I left school.
I think, I was liking it because I was resting there.
I was there, well, you know the classes at school.
It was a little difficult for me when they are like this, they put them like this.
See?
Yes.
Uh-huh, the numbers.
And I think I was practicing.
Well, it was very little time for me to do all that.
So,
My cousin, I asked my cousin and she asked me what to do.
I said, no, because then I won't know if you make them for me.
She said, well, so you can make them soon.
She said, yes, but I don't know then.
Well, but since the time was so short, I didn't learn much.
I learned a few words only.
Yes.
Bueno, siempre agarré palabras de saludar de Asina, pocas palabras.
Pues me retiré entonces y allí nos fuimos.
Entonces vino la guerra muy dura.
La guerra.
Hubo, yo creo, sería por la guerra o sería por...
that there was destruction, or I don't know what the cause would be.
The story is that they reduced our food a lot.
We had to sweeten the coffee with brown sugar.
They didn't have to give us flour.
My father, because I barely remember, because very few took us through that big street that goes straight to the sea.
There was a small shop, very small, and those were Arabs.
And those Arabs were the ones who served my father food, with and without money.
And because of so much knowledge and a lot of family, instead of giving it to my dad in secret, I think, I don't know, they would give him a grain of flour.
It was all they could give my dad, a grain of flour, because there was no flour.
And if there was, they wanted to send it to other states.
So what they did was a lot of corn flour.
They gave it to my father because the family was big.
A lot of corn flour.
And now, before, you didn't know how to make corn bread.
You made it.
I didn't make it, my mom made it.
My mom only made it because that man, Jose Jan, gave my dad a lot of Guaramilk.
And that bread, my mom beat it with a lot of Guaramilk.
And then, some pans that had legs and a...
A lid, they would put embers on top of the lid and they would put the corn bread inside that pan.
And then below, they would put embers and they would put that pan there.
And that pan would cook there.
If you would put a little heat, the golden breads would come out, but they would come out hard.
They didn't come out as fluffy as these.
Well, because they didn't have the subtleties that these have now.
Naturally, for us it was a very good bread, because we didn't know them anymore.
But it was very good, and that was what we did.
Yes, we got tired of eating it.
pero no nos morimos de hambre porque había mucha harina de maíz y mi mamá nos hacía los panes.
Y en esos sartenes, que ahora todo tiran a la basura, todo lo de años atrás lo tiran a la basura porque ahora todo es moderno, pero es más mejor lo que pasó
than what we have now.
Yes.
Both in the health of the person and in the things that are useful.
Yes.
Because what we had before was very... everything was very well built.
Yes.
From everything to everything and even in the person.
Yes.
Because now the person is like
como todos los que hay ahora.
And it has a lot of people, a lot of medicine, a lot of... a lot of... a lot of use that has happened now, both in people, in food, and in everything.
It's more modern, but now people die more than in the past years.
Yes.
And there weren't the tools that there are now.
And in the past years,
Años pasados no había lo que hay ahora.
Y ahora se muere más la gente porque ahora andamos más recio de todo.
Y por eso uno no vive en paz.
Uno vive la carrera y por eso se muere más pronto.
Porque vive la carrera.
Bueno, entonces, esto de mi...
Terminó en esto que de la escuela, al poco tiempo nos fuimos de ese lugar, de esa familia.
Nos fuimos como el veinti... Como el veinti... Como el veinticinco, yo creo, de ese lugar.
Pa'l rancho ese de José Yaliga.
We changed everything.
I think two trips to Guayín took my father to that place.
Because at that time that man was a very fat man.
He was an American man.
I don't know what race he was of.
But he had his own customs.
And his appearance made me think he was a Mexican.
He was a fat man.
His mustache was very black, a very colored man, a very fat and tall man, owner of many mules, many cows, a very large ranch that he had, and here is still his ranch.
Well, he had another ranch in Sandias.
He planted a lot of sandias there.
And he used a lot of cowboy hat.
And he was very Mexican.
His whole family, because he had big boys and girls and everything.
His oldest girl was called May.
and very good to his whole family, and a very good boss that he was with my father and everything.
So, I don't know how my father would fix it there, but my father had a lot of land.
He said that for cotton, for cabbage.
So,
My father would take care of the cows in the farm.
Every morning, at 3 or 4 in the morning, my father would be there, taking care of the cows in the farm.
He would take a lot of milk to the house.
The others would get up to have lunch with the mules, so that when they all went to work, those mules would have lunch before going to work.
All of them.
You could see the line of pure men working.
So...
At that time, my brothers worked.
My two brothers and my father.
There were three brothers who were already working.
My brothers earned a very good salary.
It was a good salary, I say, in those years.
They earned money.
They earned one peso per day.
So there were three of us.
mis tres hermanos, pero no sé si el peso por hora o el peso por día, pero más bien era el peso por día.
Bueno, tres pesos ganaban porque eran tres.
So we would get up at four in the morning to make them lunch.
They would be ready for lunch when they got up.
When they were playing, when it was dawn, my brothers and my father were already at the edge of the field.
Because in California they call it fil, here we call it labor.
Well, that was early in the morning, early in the morning.
Then, you know, my father sowed the first year and he got a lot of cabbage.
And since I was the eldest and my two brothers and my father, my mother never worked.
My mother was always at home.
No, I never worked.
Well, then, I...
I don't know what would have happened to me.
My mother didn't tell me why.
I think she didn't know.
I knew more.
I wore my brothers' pants.
My father told me, we are going to cut cabbage.
We are going to start cutting cabbage.
Soon I got ready.
and we would go, we would stick to the cart, each of us would grab our knives, there were four of us.
Here was the cart, do you know what a cart is?
It's a box.
And then two wheels.
Two wheels.
And then a mule.
Or a horse, whatever it was.
And here you were cutting the cabbage and here you were throwing it.
Here goes the other one cutting the cabbage and throwing it.
See?
And the horse walking.
So we would go out, fill up, and make cabbage.
And my brothers and I, I think that's why I like the ball.
Because if I was down, I was here, my brothers and I would throw a lot of cabbage, and cabbage, and cabbage, and cabbage, and cabbage.
And well, that was the job we did.
The whole season of cutting the cabbage, we would cut it.
So my dad made a lot of money.
Then my dad said he was going to buy a truck of the Ford that was used in those years.
He bought a Ford, a new Ford truck, because my dad always liked to buy, but good.
So he bought a truck of those.
But what I didn't like was the color, because he bought it in black.
Everything in black and black.
But it looked very pretty.
My father laughed at it.
We didn't laugh at it, not even my brothers.
My father was a driver.
And then it changed.
We, the people, there were two people who had a car.
My father bought that truck.
But our first friends were, they lived, they were John Doe workers.
It was the Cuellar family.
They bought Mr. John Donne's car.
It was a Dodge.
That was Mr. John Donne's car.
It would be his first car, I don't know.
So he bought another car, a more modern one, and he gave the car to that family.
So they were...
the family called them the rich because they already had a car and they called them the rich.
So when we bought that truck, we were the richest because that's what they called us because we didn't have any friends yet.
Only the Gonzales family had a truck.
Well, then we didn't go to Guayina anymore, to Corpos.
We would do half a day, one day to get to Corpos.
But the whole family would go to Guayina.
You see?
My father, like me, I imposed on my family.
My father would take us all and say, let's go to the store.
It was a store that was, I think it was also Arabs or Italians or I don't know.
By the way, I don't know, it's here on this big street too, which is the one that has always been full of bodies, that street.
And my father took us there.
And there, that's every year that there was money.
There he would take us and he would take us all and he would say, he would take my mother and he would take us all.
They take everything you want, everything you need to buy.
So,
Well, we didn't know what color we could look for.
We just liked whatever it was and we bought it.
My mom didn't tell us anything.
She didn't...
Mom, we like it, it's good.
My dad, it's good.
He just took us to choose.
So...
I used to buy and pay my dad a lot, because it was for everyone.
I used to buy chestnuts, beans, everything I needed.
I used to pay together, but only in one store.
It was all there.
So, for so long that I was a little older,
eh, este, el señor es el dueño de la tienda.
Tenía yo toda la confianza y decía, Lupita, es muy desgustada.
Ándale, Lupita.
Come in here and look for all the shoes you want.
Come on, you check the shoes you like, because you are very disliked.
Well, check all the ones you like.
Well, I went in there to look for the shoes I wanted.
He says, you Lupe, you are very disliked, you are never going to get married.
He says, because you, look, you don't like anything.
Well, I already checked them.
Do you like those?
Yes.
Well, we left.
We left.
So, I don't know how many years we lived there.
I went back, my sisters, my mom, I helped her a lot.
The years that I lasted, because I lasted little, but the years that I helped my mom, I worked since I was very young helping her.
I understood about my sisters, about combing them, bathing them, ironing them,
All the time my sisters were very clean.
So my father said,
The sewing machines arrived, so my father came and said, do you like the machines?
The man from the machines said to me.
I said, yes, I like them, but my father is not here right now because my mother could no longer do anything.
So I already knew a little about sewing with the neighbor.
with the neighbor.
A lady had a machine and she told me, come sew here so I can teach you.
Well, I already knew a little sewing.
So she tells me, oh, my father is coming.
Well, I'll wait for him.
My father arrives and since I was the girl who helped him a lot, both my father and my mother,
So, he tells me, his father is coming and his daughter wants a machine.
So my father tells my mother, hey, do you want a machine?
And my mother says,
Well, no, he says, why do you want this machine?
Why do you want a new machine?
It costs a lot.
He says, why don't you better buy a used one so that it can be taught?
And then my father says, no.
He says, if she wants a machine, it's better to buy her a new machine.
And then I told him, I already know how to sew.
I told him, if you want to buy me a machine, Dad, buy me a new machine.
I do want a machine.
He said, yes.
Do you want the new machine?
Yes.
Well, my mom didn't say anything anymore because she said, no, it's better to buy her a new sewing machine.
So I said, I already know how to sew.
Well, then let's buy it.
And then they bought me a new sewing machine.
My dad didn't buy it, it didn't cost the machine anything more than, it seems to me, 100 pesos.
It didn't cost much in those years of that Singer.
On that machine, I didn't let my mom sew.
Because we sewed by hand.
We sewed everything by hand.
My mother taught me how to sew by hand, but she wanted me to sew very well, like a machine.
And if I didn't sew well, I did sew well.
I knew I sewed well, but she didn't like it.
She would say, sew it well again.
Well, I sewed it again.
I sewed it again.
So when they bought that machine for me,
I sewed for my mother, because my mother gave the clothes to sew, they charged 50 cents for sewing the clothes, but it was not money, because I sewed them.
So they say,
So I sewed everything in the machine, I didn't let her sew everything.
I cut her dresses and sewed all her dresses in the machine.
So from there we went back to the same place where we had been born.
Because that Italian family had already left their place.
They had already gone to another place because they were already old men.
But all of these places are close to here, to Corpus?
Yes.
Yes, they are close.
Yes, yes, all of these, where we have lived, yes, everything is close here.
Yes, in the Nueces County.
Yes, it's in Condado de Nueces, everything I'm talking about.
Everything is in Condado de Nueces.
Yes, yes.
You never lived there.
I didn't know anything about Robestown.
No, you didn't come to California or places like that.
Well, you know that now, since I got married, since I got married, I've been to other states.
Yes, but in the past.
Ah, not in the past, no.
I've been here since my dad...
Y toda nuestra familia aquí estuvimos, todo el tiempo aquí estuvimos, porque él nunca salió de aquí.
Bueno, entonces volvimos a regresar para atrás.
Le volvieron a dar el mismo lugar a mi papá de tierra.
But then we were better off because we already had a truck.
And then my brothers, who were my two brothers, my father, who is in this place where he bought the machine for me, he bought my brothers two horses, beautiful horses, and two
Because they wanted to ride horses and they couldn't buy so many cars.
But horses, yes.
So my brothers, each one went out to walk on their horses because they lived here.
They had to come here where they had their friends and my grandmother.
So here was my grandmother and my grandmother.
They would come on Saturdays and they would be here and they would go back until Sunday afternoon.
That's why they wanted their horses and very good chairs.
So when we came back to that place, I was 16 years old.
My older sister was older, but she was
I was with my grandmother, she had been raised with my grandmother, the sister who followed me.
But since she was already old, she wanted to be next to us.
Because she was not forced to be alone, just with my grandmother.
And here in my house there were many little sisters and I was the oldest and she had never been with us.
She said, I want to be with mom.
I don't want to be with grandma anymore.
But when grandma was alone, mom left her there.
But my mom wanted her to leave and my sister didn't want to go.
Poor thing, she was alone in the mountains.
She wasn't well.
She didn't want to be there.
So that house was as big as this one.
of the Italian men, of Mr. Rosas.
So, that's where we lived.
I think I was about six years old, six months old, when I thought of getting married.
So,
So I came back and I thought about getting married.
Naturally, when you're a father, you feel bad.
I was the first one.
My father was very mortified and very hurt, but my father didn't say anything.
But he did feel bad.
The one who told my mother and the one who told my father was her.
So I got married.
El 27.
¿En qué modo encontró con su esposo?
Mi esposo era de... Él era de México.
From Mexico?
From which part?
He was from Monterrey.
Yes, his whole family was there in Monterrey.
And he passed with papers to this side.
And here he was.
There he was working in that ranch too.
There he taught himself to work.
And well, in that ranch I met him.
And one, I don't know, one no longer thinks, there are things that one doesn't think about when one is still old.
And there are still things that one doesn't think about.
In what year did your husband come to the United States?
I think he came around...
I think it was around...
I'm not very sure, but I think it was around...
I think he came around... around 23, 24.
I'm not very sure.
For what reason?
For what reason did he come?
Oh, well, he came for the same reasons that there is not much life there because the jobs are not like here.
Not many have the opportunities.
Now there are many opportunities.
In those years there were not the opportunities that there are now.
Now there are people who are very poor.
Now there are people who don't have a school.
Now there are people who don't have education.
It's because they don't want it.
Now they have all the opportunities.
And Mexico too?
Mexico, yes, there are also opportunities because I have been to Monterrey, I have been to Monterrey twice.
And now that I have been alone with my children, I have been twice before.
And I have seen that there are very poor people, but most of the people have
their jobs, and very good jobs that many people in Mexico have.
The poorest people have very good jobs to maintain themselves.
Because they sell their things that they sell, very pretty, and any of those things need to be studied.
And they have them, that's why they learn them, and that's why they make their lives.
But I'm going to tell you that Mexico, as you know, I only know it because I've heard it and because they tell me about it.
But yes, Mexico is very rich.
As they say, Mexico is sitting in gold.
But yes,
What's the point of me being very rich and having the money saved here?
You don't put it to work for the poor.
You don't put it to help your own people.
No.
You want to have it.
You use it a lot.
You just think about being well.
In having everything, only you.
You have everything, you don't know about the others.
And that's what I see, that it's not right.
Because having your money, why don't you put it to work?
So that that family doesn't suffer, the poorest one like you, doesn't suffer.
put it to work and you will see how there is no poverty.
Even if it is a little, like here when the United States started to pay little by little, but people knew how to support themselves.
Well, there should have been
Like those who have so much money, put them to work so that those poor people don't suffer.
Many of those people have died, many, in these states.
Why?
Because there are many who have a lot of family and they don't have to keep them.
And that's why they come to these places.
because the money is saved there from those who have it, they don't give them what they lack.
That's what I take badly there.
And Yacina is, because I say on my part, I have gone a little, here to Laredo, here to Laredo, this to Monterrey,
Yo tengo todo esto que no uso.
Yo fui la otra vez.
Yo llevé como cuatro o cinco paquetes.
Yo los anduve repartiendo allí a esa gente que está de atiro pobre.
Yo no lo necesito.
Yo se los llevé a ellos.
Porque a mí, yo no quiero tirar esto y tirar lo otro.
Nosotros tenemos abastecido aquí, gracias a Dios.
Bueno.
We don't like it anymore.
We don't like this food anymore.
Everything.
No, if God punishes us too.
That's not good.
If you go... Look, there are times when I have penises.
I'm collecting penises, penises, penises.
I have many penises, or nickels, or whatever.
I carry many nickels in my wallet.
I take them out with all the people I see who need nickels.
I give it to them.
I'm not going to be richer if I give a nickel and a dime.
That's not going to help me.
No.
What I have is good.
I don't envy anyone.
I don't envy anything.
Because I don't have those years.
I don't envy anything.
Nothing good.
I go there, I tell you, I give away all the packages, packages, packages of clothes, of what I carry there.
I give it to the poor people.
I give the money to the poor people.
That's why I carry what I carry loose to give away.
I am here, where I can earn a nickel.
Yo aquí estoy, yo hago mis costuras, yo hago mis delantares, yo hago horquilleros.
¿Yo puedo ganar un peso?
Allá no.
Esa gente no tiene, no tiene dinero para comprar un pedazo de material porque no lo tienen.
Bueno, entonces, yo si lo tengo, ahorita no lo tengo, al ratito lo tengo y allá no.
¿Ves?
Porque ellos no tienen con qué ponerse a trabajar, monchos.
And that's what makes a lot of money.
It's like me, I'm doing very well here, I have everything here.
Those people need a piece of bread, and I'm eating it.
I don't need poverty, I'm not in poverty, I'm not in anything.
I'm living very peacefully and everything.
I don't know about the others.
And that's what's not good.
That's not good, and I'm not right about that.
So, I got married on the 27th.
I got married.
Well, I got out of my house well because
I didn't think about it.
It was hard for me and all that.
I thought, my mom and dad put in four months for me to get married.
Well, I waited because I said, if they don't say yes, well, I'm going to stay.
So, the year came, my little boy.
He is now 40 years old.
He is the oldest and he is in the service.
Well, nine of my family came.
There are nine of my children.
Five men and three women.
So I...
The first time I went to the West, I went here nearby.
The first time I went out, it was with my boy when he went to the service.
Because my boy said, Mom, I'm going to go to the service.
He said, he registered when he was 18 years old, which was when the war was.
In this second war.
The World War II.
The World War II.
Then he told me, Mom, we've never gone out of here.
And I want us to go to Las Piscas this year, he said, because I'm going to leave next month.
So I had my bad dad, and I had my mom and my grandparents who had died.
Mi abuelito murieron el 37, murió mi abuelito.
Y el 45 murió mi abuelita.
Y el 45 mismo se fue mi muchacho al servicio.
Pues que entonces yo, cuando yo,
Cuando yo me casé, yo pensé nunca irme de fuera de ellos.
Porque yo pensé todo el tiempo, si yo me casaba, estar todo el tiempo al lado de ellos.
Pero entonces cuando yo, mi muchacho me dijo que me fuera, mi papá estaba malo.
Y yo fui y le dije a mi papá que yo me iba a retirar de aquí.
Y que me iba a ir.
to the north.
So my father says to me, well, I'm happy that you're leaving with your family, because I know that you're not having a good life.
And maybe you can get a little better so that the boys can help you and you can leave.
Well, I didn't feel very good leaving because my father was sick.
But my Lord had promised me all the time that He would never take me out of my parents' side.
But He never knew this.
But that's how it was.
He did fulfill what He told me.
But because of Him, I lost my father because I never saw him again.
Because on that trip, I lost him.
But who caused it?
Well, it was him.
Because if he had seen the states with so many people at ease, I wouldn't have left this state.
So we went.
Thank God, we went back.
I never received a telegram from my father.
I never heard from him.
Until I was on the ground, I knew that my father had died.
It was impossible to come because they had buried him.
So I went back.
My son had the opportunity to go to Monterrey.
to see his uncles, because his whole family is there.
Yes.
Then he said, Mom, give me money to go see my uncles.
Yes.
And he went with his cousin to Monterrey.
A week passed and he came back.
Then he went to the service.
Then the second one stayed, the one who followed him.
Que fue mi muchacho.
